sec.p:
Genome-scale transcriptional profiling studies and allelic expression patterns also identify considerable variation lacking an obvious genetic source (
  Brem et al. 2002; 
  Cheung et al. 2003; 
  Schadt et al. 2003). However, tracking down a source as purely epigenetic is severely limited if not impossible when working with outbred populations because of the abundant supply of genetic variation and the difficulties in controlling confounding factors such as environment or allelic transcript stability. Furthermore, the intent of most studies is to quantify genetic causes of gene expression variation between tissues, individuals, or populations. Thus, the study designs will not be sensitive detectors of epigenetic effects, despite showing there is potential for widespread epigenetic regulation of gene expression. It may be possible to gain an idea of the genome-wide impact of epigenetic transcriptional effects by transcriptional profiling studies within inbred strains of animals, under defined environmental conditions.
